<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, June 14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME -- Two Italian generals, who were former commanders of
Italian troops on the peacekeeping mission in Somalia, have been
relieved of their current duties following allegations that their
troops tortured and killed civilian Somalis.
</P>
<P>
General Bruno Loi and General Carmine Fiore had asked to be
allowed to step down so as to "ease and speed up the investigation
underway", a statement from the office of the Army Chief of Staff
said.
</P>
<P>
ALGIERS -- Algerian President Liamine Zeroual reappointed today
outgoing Prime Minister Ahmed Ouyahia as head of of the new
government of the country.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Ouyahia, who had been prime minister of the north African
nation since January, 1996, formally resigned Tuesday in order to
clear the way for the formation of a new government after last
week's parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
HARARE -- Diplomats have been accused of smuggling ivory into
Japan, the world's largest consumer of elephant ivory, the
Zimbabwe News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The International Environmental Investigation Agency (EIA) said
46 seizures of illegal ivory imports had been made in Japan
between 1989 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- More than one in every four recent graduates from
universities in the Netherlands do not have jobs, a report by
Dutch job centers says.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment rates for recent college graduates rose two
percentage points to 29 percent last year, compared with a 17
percent rate for vocational school leavers.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- The U.S. resolution to recognize Jerusalem as the
capital of Israel and to move the U.S. embassy from Tel Aviv to
the city is aimed at encouraging Israeli aggression, the local
Syrian daily Teshreen said today.
</P>
<P>
The paper pointed out in its commentary that the resolution
does not affect the identity of Jerusalem in the least but it
has adverse effects on the Middle East peace process and the
credibility of the United States as well as its interests in the
region.
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Pakistan Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan has
stated that his country might go to an American court to seek a
refund of 628 million U.S. dollars it paid for the purchase of
F-16 aircraft, according to the official Associated Press of
Pakistan (APP) today.
</P>
<P>
Ayub Khan told APP two days ago that this might be the best
choice for the Pakistani government because it has fallen through
to get the refund through aircraft sale to a third country.
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- French President Jacques Chirac today inaugurated the
annual Bourget Aeronautics and Space Saloon, the world's biggest
airspace industrial exhibition, at the Bourget airport, northeast
of Paris.
</P>
<P>
This year's Bourget airspace show coincided with a rise in sale
of planes and other airspace products in the global market, as
well as an increasingly fierce competition between European and
American airspace groups.
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- The operation rate of South Korea's domestic auto
industry is expected to keep falling throughout the next four
years, the Korea Automobile Manufacturers Association and Kia
Motors Corporation said today.
</P>
<P>
The country's car output rate is expected to fall from 80.1
percent last year to 72.9 percent this year and 53.9 percent by
the year 2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
