<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Premiere of "Opium War" Held in South China Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUMEN, GUANGDONG, June 14 (Xinhua) -- The premiere of "The
Opium War," an epic Chinese film depicting Britain's
opium-peddling in China and the ceding of Hong Kong, was held
tonight in Humen Town of Dongguan City, in south China's Guangdong
Province.
</P>
<P>
Set in June of 1839, the film tells the story of the Chinese
Emperor's Special Envoy Lin Zexu, who confiscated and burned over
20,000 cases of opium from British traders. The Opium War which
resulted from this incident was fought in Humen.
</P>
<P>
The film's director, Xie Jin, attended the premiere in Humen,
together with a crowd of more than 2,000.
</P>
<P>
Zhong Ganquan, head of the town, said tonight that the filming
of the movie began in Humen on June 14, 1996, and it is even more
significant to hold the premiere there with Hong Kong's return
approaching.
</P>
<P>
The film recounts the unyielding and heroic spirit of the
Chinese people in fighting against foreign invasion, Zhong said.
</P>
<P>
Bao Guo'an, who plays "Lin Zexu" in the film, praised the Humen
people's courage against foreign invaders during the war and
thanked them for their support for filming the movie over the past
year.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
