<DOCNO> XIE19970615.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Defense Secretary Visits Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen arrived in Saudi Arabia today to start a Gulf tour, the
first in his current capacity.
</P>
<P>
According to the Kuwait News Agency (Kuna), Cohen is expected
to hold talks with the Gulf leaders on the latest developments in
the region and deliver a message of the U.S. determination to
maintain security of its Arab allies in the region.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival in the Saudi red-sea coast city of Jeddah,
Cohen was greeted by Saudi Second Deputy Prime Minister and
Minister of Defense, Prince Sultan Bin Abdel Aziz, and other
senior officials.
</P>
<P>
He will meet with Saudi King Fahd Bin Abdul Aziz and hold his
second meeting since last February's meet in Washington with his
Saudi counterpart Prince Sultan on issues of security in the Gulf
and the U.S. commitment to it, especially concerning the
U.S. policy of "dual containment," as well as bilateral military
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
They would also discuss the developments in the Middle East
peace process and the efforts to revive it, the Turkish incursion
in northern Iraq and joint defense programs.
</P>
<P>
Kuna said quoting informed sources that Prince Sultan would
convey to Cohen his government's concern about the current
deadlock in the peace process and the recent U.S. congress
decision to move the U.S. embassy in Israel from Tel Aviv to
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Cohen and Prince Sultan will also discuss the progress in
measures to protect the 4,000 U.S. troops in Saudi Arabia from
terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed several months ago to redeploy these
troops outside cities following two explosions in Riyadh and
Khobar in November 1995 and June 1996 respectively that claimed
the lives of 24 U.S. servicemen.
</P>
<P>
Cohen will also head to Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates
before returning to Washington, official sources said, adding that
his initial schedule also include Bahrain and Oman but later
canceled because of other engagements.
</P>
<P>
This is his first visit as defense secretary to the
strategically important and oil-rich Gulf where the U.S. maintains
a major naval presence as well as warplanes that keep watching
over southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has promised to protect its Gulf Arab allies from any
security threats from abroad. Sources here said that during his Gulf
tour, Cohen would lobby for U.S. firms seeking arms sales to Gulf
Arab states with offers of the most sophisticated weapon systems
that money can buy.
</P>
<P>
The talks between Cohen and his Saudi counterpart would also
touch on the Kingdom's plan to purchase U.S. F-16 jet fighters to
replace the old F-5 warplanes, reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
