<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish, Indonesian Presidents Stress Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Istanbul, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel and his Indonesian counterpart Suharto met here today with
both expressing the hope to further strengthen bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry spokesman Omer Akbel told Xinhua that
in a 30-minute meeting here today both presidents believed that
Turkey and Indonesia have strong bonds and great potentials for
closer cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Demirel and Suharto, who is here to attend the D-8 Group
summit scheduled for Sunday, are eager to give new impetus to the
activities in joint ventures and trade expansion between the two
two countries, Akbel said.
</P>
<P>
Suharto appreciated Turkey's invitation for participating in
the D-8 Group summit in Istanbul, the largest city of Turkey, the
spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
The D-8 Group, which was launched by Turkey after the Islamic
Welfare Party led by Turkish Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan came
to power last summer, will be officially inaugurated at the Sunday
summit.
</P>
<P>
The Muslim countries' group consists of Turkey, Iran, Egypt,
Nigeria, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Malaysia as well as Indonesia,
enjoying a roughly 800 million population and a combined 600
billion U.S. dollar GNP.
</P>
<P>
The Sunday D-8 Group summit will discuss ways to further boost
cooperation among the member states; and the establishment of a
general secretariat is expected to be one of several main subjects
on the agenda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
