<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Refuses UN Observer at Har Homa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Israel has informed the UN that
it would not receive a representative sent to observe the building
activities at Har Homa (Jabal Abu Ghneim), Israel Radio said here
today.
</P>
<P>
UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan was due to send an official
to Israel today as part of a UN General Assembly decision
calling on Israel to cease the construction of the new Jewish
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
Israel rejected the decision as "out of place," saying the UN
was ignoring a number of crisis and problems occurring elsewhere
in the world.
</P>
<P>
In March, following the start of the construction at Har Homa,
there were two UN Security Council debates and one in the assembly
on the controversial construction.
</P>
<P>
In the UN Security Council, the United States twice vetoed
resolutions that would have assailed Israel for the building
project on the southeastern outskirts of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Political and security contacts between Israel and the
Palestinians have been suspended since March when Israel ordered
the new Jewish settlement building go ahead despite widespread
opposition.
</P>
<P>
Palestinians have said that Israel must stop the construction
before peace talks can resume, while Israel insists the
Palestinian Authority crack down on terror and reestablish full
security cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
