<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Namibian Prime Minister Lashes at Western </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Namibian Prime Minister Hage
Geingob today lashed out at the western countries for giving
priority to the lives of animals over those of humans and
dictating how Africa should manage its wildlife.
</P>
<P>
''They have killed all their wildlife and now they want to
tell us how to look after ours,'' he said during a tour of the
Matopos National Park of Zimbabwse.
</P>
<P>
Namibia, like Zimbabwe and Botswana, has a vast elephant
population and is battling at the ongoing 10th Convention on
International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES) conference here
to try to allow restricted trade in the animal's products and
benefit the communities.
</P>
<P>
Namibia has stockpiles of ivory which, like its neighbours, it
has been unable to sell because of the CITES ban on the trade.
</P>
<P>
Hage Geingob said there is need to cull the elephants which
are endangering the lives of people, killing them, destroying
their crops and causing habitat degradation in the three
countries.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his satisfaction with the support being given
to the three countries' proposal with the Southern Africa
Development Community (SADC) having agreed to speak with one voice
at the conference.
</P>
<P>
It is, however, unfortunate that some of the countries which
are against the proposal are powerful and could abuse their
power, he said.
</P>
<P>
Geingob is here on a five-day official visit and will leave
Zimbabwe on Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
