<DOCNO> XIE19970615.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Delegates Warned Not to Carry Ivory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 14 (Xinhua) -- European delegates attending the
ongoing 10th CITES Conference here have been warned that they
risk prosecution back in their countries if they brought back
souvenirs made from products of protected species.
</P>
<P>
TRAFFIC, the joint wildlife trade monitoring agency of the
Worldwide Fund for Nature and the International Union for the
Conservation of Nature, has said that starting this month,
countries of the European Union (EU) were required to impose a
system of national penalties to combat illegal wildlife trade.
</P>
<P>
In a document circulated to about 1,500 delegates from 138
countries participating in the two-week CITES Conference, TRAFFIC
said that although international trade in ivory was banned in
1989, carvings could still be found legally sold, particularly in
Africa and Asia.
</P>
<P>
''Bringing home chess pieces made of ivory could cost you more
than your holiday,'' warned TRAFFIC.
</P>
<P>
''Do not be tempted to return home with ivory. It is
illegal,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
TRAFFIC also warned against bringing into EU countries
jewellery or sunglasses made from tortoise shell.
</P>
<P>
Sea turtle shell items including whole shells, stuffed
animals, jewellery, combs and sunglasses could not be legally
brought into the EU and therefore would be confiscated.
</P>
<P>
Not only animal products from protected species are proscribed
in the EU, certain wild flora is also on the list.
</P>
<P>
The agency also pointed out that over 800 species of animals
and plants are currently banned from international commercial
trade and more than 20,000 others are controlled under the
European Law implementing the convention on international trade
in endangered species. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
