<DOCNO> XIE19970615.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nujoma's Third Term Special to Him: Says Namibian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Namibian Prime Minister
Hage Geingob today said the extension of President Sam Nujoma's
rule to a third five-year term was ''special just for the
nation's founder'' and his successors would serve only two terms.
</P>
<P>
While the move required an amendment to the constitution,
Geingob said, this would apply only to Nujoma who was the
nation's founder, and leaders to succeed him would have to revert
to the current constitution which limits leaders' terms to two.
</P>
<P>
The Namibian Prime Minister noted that it was necessary to
extend Nujoma's term of office because 10 years was too short to
complete the work he had initiated.
</P>
<P>
The majority of Namibians, he said, felt that changing leaders
now would derail some processes such as tribal and racial
reconciliation as well as peace which Nujoma had brought to the
southern African nation.
</P>
<P>
The nation's ruling party, South West African People's
Organisation (SWAPO) congress recently decided to elect Nujoma
for a third term, arousing fears that the country was becoming
like other African states which had leaders for life.
</P>
<P>
Geingob however, dispelled these fears, saying Nujoma was
SWAPO's choice but would stand against other opposition
candidates in the elections, hence they would be democratic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970615.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Condemns US Congress Decision on Embassy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait National Assembly
today condemned the U.S. congress's decision to move the
American embassy in Israel to Jerusalem and asked President
Bill Clinton to overrun the decision.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after a parliamentary session, the
National Assembly expressed grave concern over the decision
which it said would lead the region to "a turmoil of
violence."
</P>
<P>
It said Kuwaiti parliament hoped the Clinton administration
would be able to overrun the congress decision to move the
U.S. embassy from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem, especially in the
current circumstances and as a sign of respect to Muslims around
the globe.
</P>
<P>
It described the decision as "a blow to peace efforts in
the region and a declaration of war against the Palestinians
who would not accept any peace depriving them from their
legitimate rights."
</P>
<P>
The statement said the congress decision would undermine the
international and U.S. efforts to save the peace process from
the setback it suffered due to Israel's stubborn policies.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. congress made the decision recently amid the
international criticism and Arab attacks against Israeli
insistence on construction of a new Jewish settlement in East
Jerusalem it occupied from the Arab people.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli hardline policy has led the Middle East peace
process into a deadlock and roused frequent violence in the
disputed holy city where the Palestinians are struggling to make
it as their capital city of a Palestinian state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
