<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-14 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Privatization Spurs Egyptian Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 14 (Xinhua) -- The share of the private sector in
Egypt's economic activities has increased from 39 percent in the
early 1980s, to 55 percent in 1996-97, Egyptian Minister of
Economy and International Cooperation Nawal Tatawy said today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the private sector's contribution to the gross
domestic product increased from 51 percent to 67 percent, Tatawy
said while addressing a seminar organized by Egyptian National
Bank.
</P>
<P>
"The private sector has already started to restore its role in
economic development since market economy policies were adopted,"
she added.
</P>
<P>
Since 1981 when the Investment Law was first introduced, about
5,183 projects have been established by December 1996, against
1,416 projects five years earlier, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
The banking system has played a vital role in helping privatize
the state-run enterprises and bring about new ones, Tatawy added.
</P>
<P>
The total investments during the fourth five year plan period
(1997-2002) are expected to hit about 400 billion Egyptian pounds
(about 117 billion U.S. dollars), Tatawy said.
</P>
<P>
Increased investments in the private sector have spurred annual
GDP growth rate to 5.5 percent last year, from 1.9 percent when
privatization began, Tatawy said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has privatized earnestly since President Hosni Mubarak
set up a reform-minded cabinet in 1996, five years after launching
the privatization drive to reduce government involvement in the
economy.
</P>
<P>
Egypt will have sold shares by the end of this year of a third
of the companies it has promised to privatize under its economic
reform program.
</P>
<P>
Public Sector Minister Atef Obeid said earlier that Egypt so
far has sold shares in 68 companies with a total value of 5
billion pounds (1.5 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Obeid said shares in 20 more companies will be listed in Egyptian
Stock Exchange by the end of June, and another 20 by the year's end,
raising the total to 108. Egypt has promised to privatize more
than 300 state-owned companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
