<HEADLINE> Teenager Confesses to German Church Arson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 14 (Xinhua) -- A 19-year-old gardening apprentice
has confessed to having set on fire a Catholic church in the
northern German city of Luebeck last month, motivated by
xenophobic sentiment, investigators said today.
</P>
<P>
An arrest warrant had already been issued for the offender on
Friday evening, police said.
</P>
<P>
A special police investigating team linked the arson attack to
a group of five young people who had been seen in the area of the
St. Vicelin church in Luebeck at about 1 a.m. on May 25 when the
arson took place.
</P>
<P>
According to the police, a 15-year-old and a 17-year-old of the
group later admitted to smearing the church's wall with swastikas
and the name of a Luebeck pastor who recently gave shelter to a
family of Algerian immigrants in his parish.
</P>
<P>
The 15-year-old then blamed his 19-year-old brother of having
set the church on fire, police added.
</P>
<P>
The 19-year-old eventually confessed to the crime, admitting
that he broke into a shed next to the church and shot at a gas
canister inside with a starting pistol. The fire then spread from
the shed to the church, almost completely gutting it.
</P>
<P>
Police said the two youths aged 15 and 17 had been released
from their custody, but still remained suspects. The other two
members of the group were thought not to have been directly
involved in the attack.
</P>
<P>
Luebeck has hit the headlines several times in the past few
years with arson attacks on targets such as Jewish synagogs and
foreign refugee homes. A majority of the incidents have been
linked to right extremists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
