<HEADLINE> UK Leading Supermarket Chains to Ban Alcopops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Britain's two supermarket chains
announced that all alcopops would be taken of their shelves from
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The move by the Co-op Retail Trading Group, with 1,200 stores
and Iceland, with 600 branches, came on the day that Prime
Minister Tony Blair signaled Friday a crackdown on manufacturers
which tempt under-age drinkers.
</P>
<P>
On the previous day Health Secretary Frank Dobson made a strong
attack on alcopop manufacturers, saying they were deliberately
trying to get children addicted to alcohol.
</P>
<P>
Bill Shannon, head of corporate affairs for the Co-op, said,
"As a responsible retailer, we feel the time has come to act."
</P>
<P>
"We believe these drinks are designed to appeal to young people
and are largely consumed by under-18s who cannot legally buy
them," he added.
</P>
<P>
Malcomlm Walker, the chairman of Iceland, said the move had
been prompted by customer concern. "While commercially this
decision will hurt, as a family company we must act responsibly
and reflect the views of customers," Walker added.
</P>
<P>
Although other stores are urged to join the ban, Sainsbury's,
Tesco and Safeway all said they would continue selling alcopops.
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman for Sainsbury's said, "We don't make moral
decisions on behalf of our customers. Where there is a demand for
a product, we believe customers should have a choice."
</P>
<P>
Tesco announced a package of measures aimed at reassuring
customers about the sale of alcopops, including a ban on alcoholic
milks and sachets.
</P>
<P>
Safeway said that it had "a very responsible attitude" to the
sale of alcopops and staff were trained to request identification
if they thought a purchaser could be under 18.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts believe that no matter what attitude a
supermarket takes, the move taken by the Co-op and Iceland will
add to the pressure on drinks manufacturers to stop producing the
drinks or to introduce stricter controls on their sale. 
</P>
</TEXT>
