<HEADLINE> Trial of Israeli Spy Adjourned Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 14 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian Higher State Security
Court today adjourned till Tuesday the trial of an Israeli textile
worker and an Egyptian charged of spying for the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
The 180-minute trial started this morning under tight security
with Azam Azam, a 35-year-old chief mechanic at an Israeli-owned
factory in Egypt, and his Egyptian colleague, 34-year-old Emad
Abdul Hamid Ismail attending.
</P>
<P>
The two, arrested in November, again pleaded their innocence
to charges of spying for the Jewish state that can carry sentences
of life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
Two Israeli women, Zahra Yousef Greis and Mona Ahmed Shawahna,
who are at large in Israel, were tried in absentia as in the
previous two hearings of the case that opened on April 24.
</P>
<P>
The defense attorney Faird al-Dib, at the beginning thanked the
court for allowing him to defend Azam.
</P>
<P>
Dib, a well-known Egyptian lawyer, was punched by his Egyptian
colleague after the court adjourned its second hearing of the case
on May 18.
</P>
<P>
He has been under harsh criticism for the last few weeks. The
Cairo Bar Association has ordered him to appear before its
disciplinary commission on June 11 for agreeing to defend the
Israeli without notifying the syndicate.
</P>
<P>
Policemen in riot gear were deployed inside and outside the
courtroom in the Bab el-Khalq area, downtown of the capital.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is the first Arab country to have a peace treaty with
Israel but ties have been cool. The spy case, however, added to
the tensions because of the Mideast peace deadlock. 
</P>
