<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls for Race Relations Improvement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today launched a year-long campaign against intolerance by urging
black and white America to "breach racial divides."
</P>
<P>
Clinton denounced California's anti-affirmative action drive as
"dramatic and devastating."
</P>
<P>
In stern rebuke to ending racial preferences, Clinton said,
"Call it what you will, but I call it resegregation."
</P>
<P>
In a commencement address at the University of California in
San Diego, Clinton sought to trace the history of race relations
in America and offer a frank assessment of where matters now
stand.
</P>
<P>
"The ideals that bind us together are as old as our nation, but
so are the forces that would pull us apart," Clinton was quoted by
media reports as saying to the graduates.
</P>
<P>
Recalling struggles for civil rights in the South, the
president said, "We have torn down the barriers in our laws. Now
we must break down the barriers in our lives, our minds and our
hearts."
</P>
<P>
Clinton's chose California as the site of his speech on race
relations to underscore his opposition to Proposition 209, a 1996
ban on racial preferences. In 1995, the University of California
system, including the campus he visited Saturday, ended
affirmative action in admissions.
</P>
<P>
Proposition 209, approved by California voters in November,
bans consideration of race and gender in state hiring, contracting
and education. It has not taken effect because of legal
challenges, which the Justice Department has supported in briefs
to the federal courts.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has criticized university systems in California and
Texas for ending affirmative action for admission. The number of
blacks admitted to the University of California's Boalt Hall law
school tumbled 81 percent in the first year without affirmative
action, and Hispanic admissions fell 50 percent
</P>
<P>
"I know that many people in California voted to repeal
affirmative action, and did so without ill motive. But the results
are dramatic and devastating," Clinton said. "Enrollments in law
school and other graduate programs are plummeting for the first
time in decades."
</P>
<P>
With the help of an advisory board formed earlier and its 15-
to 20-member staff, Clinton has promised to start a national
discussion about racial, religious and ethnic tensions in America.
The president is expected to come up with concrete solutions in a
report to the American public in a year.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has also promised to devote at least one major
presidential event on the topic.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We know what we will look like -- but what will we be
like? Can we be one America, respecting, even celebrating our
differences, but embracing more strongly what we have in common?"
</P>
<P>
"Our hearts long to answer yes, but our history reminds us that
it will be hard," Clinton said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
