<HEADLINE> Clinton Reaffirms Necessity of China's MFN Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 14 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton today
used his weekly radio speech to repeat his call for the renewal of
the Most Favored Nation (MFN) trade status for China.
</P>
<P>
"One thing we must not do is take any measures that would
weaken Hong Kong," Clinton said in his five-minute radio speech.
"No step would more clearly harm Hong Kong than reversing the
course we have followed for years by denying normal trading status
to China."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that the United States has a big economic interest
in a smooth transition in Hong Kong because more than 1,100 U.S.
firms operate there, "making it the heart of American business in
the fastest-growing part of the world."
</P>
<P>
He argued that shrinking ties with China would derail
U.S.-China efforts to combat drug trafficking, and jeopardize U.S.
jobs dependent on the emerging market.
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced the best way to promote our interests and our
values is not to shut China out, but to draw China in," the
president said.
</P>
<P>
"If we treat China as our enemy, we may create the very outcome
we're trying to guard against," he said. 
</P>
