<HEADLINE> SADC Energy Action Plan Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 14 (Xinhua) --The energy ministers meeting
of the Southern African Development Community (SADC) held in
Arusha, northern Tanzania today approved a Energy Action Plan to
implement agreed projects and strengthen co-operation among
members states.
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here, the ministers in their
one-day meeting noted that SADC had developed many projects and
programs without successful realisation or with limited results.
</P>
<P>
The ministers stressed the need to "realise the agreed
projects and bring faster economic development in the region".
</P>
<P>
The action plan derives from the strategies defined in the
SADC energy sector co-operation and strategy document.
</P>
<P>
The ministers reviewed the financing energy services for Small
Scale Energy Users (FINESSE) project and noted that phase one of
the program covering Lesotho, South Africa and Zimbabwe has been
completed while phase two embracing Angola, Malawi and Namibia
will be initiated soon.
</P>
<P>
The main objective of FINESSE is to facilitate the financing
of renewable energy and energy conservation measures by financial
institutions, international aid agencies, government and private
sector.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, chaired by Albian Assis of Angola, chairperson of
the SADC energy ministers committee, was aware of the slow
response by member states in submitting energy data for the 1998
energy statistics yearbook.
</P>
<P>
However, the ministers were satisfied with the progress
achieved so far in the energy sector since the creation of the
SADC energy co-operation in 1993, although much more is left to
be done.
</P>
<P>
The next SADC energy ministers meeting is scheduled for
Zimbabwe in June next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
