<HEADLINE> Nepali Lower House Demands Lower Oil Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The finance committee of the
Nepali lower house today adopted a resolution demanding that the
government act immediately to reduce the prices of kerosene,
diesel, gas and cooking gas.
</P>
<P>
The resolution said considering the serious impact of the price
hike on the daily life of the consumers, the government should
take immediate action to lower the prices.
</P>
<P>
The committee also decided to invite the minister for supplies
and the general manager of Nepal Oil Corporation (NOC) to its next
meeting for necessary discussions.
</P>
<P>
Under the new price structure set by the NOC effective from
last Friday, gas is now sold for 39 rupees per liter, up five
rupees, diesel for 17.5 rupees, up 3.5 rupees, and kerosene for 11
rupees, up 1.5 rupees.
</P>
<P>
Since then, complaints have been heard all over Nepal. Some are
worried that the rise in petroleum products may lead to higher
prices for other daily necessities.
</P>
<P>
The Federation of Nepalese Transport Entrepreneurs has warned
that if the government does not withdraw its decision immediately,
it will increase transportation fares by 35 to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
The NOC has said that it had no other choice because in the
past eight to nine months, it has suffered a loss of 490 million
rupees (about 8.5 million U.S. dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
