<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Loans Iran to Protect Ozone Layer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations has granted 17
million U.S. dollars to Iran for eliminating substances that
destroy the ozone layer, local Persian daily Jomhuri Islami
reported today.
</P>
<P>
This is part of a worldwide effort of the UN to stop the use of
CFCs, accused of thinning the ozone layer that protects the earth
from excessive ultraviolet radiation, during the period from 1996
to 2005.
</P>
<P>
Nasser Moharram Nezhad, deputy president for Human Habitat of
Iran's Ecological Organization, said "by implementing plans aimed
at reconstructing the ozone layer, all the substances that play a
role in destroying the ozone layer will be eliminated from the
cycle of industrial and chemical products."
</P>
<P>
The official said that these plans were implemented in 1996
in the industrialized countries and will be fully implemented in
developing countries by the year 2005 with UN assistance.
</P>
<P>
Iran has pledged that it would reach the defined aims of this
program in 1999, about six years ahead of the schedule for
developing countries, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
