<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier Zou Jiahua Inspects Gansu Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier Zou Jiahua has called
on local officials in northwest China's Gansu Province to further
emancipate their minds and make practical efforts to push forward
economic growth in the country's central and western areas.
</P>
<P>
During his inspection tour in Gansu from June 11 to 15, Zou
expressed appreciation for good water conservation measures to
improve farming conditions, saying that water problem has been the key
factor to holding economic growth in northwest China.
</P>
<P>
Local officials and the masses have been active in constructing
both large and small water conservation projects, and they have
found a feasible way out for agricultural development and poverty
eradication in the mountainous areas through building terraced
fields, collecting rain water, and employing trickle and spray
irrigation.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier noted that in the mountainous areas, it is
important to map out an overall plan to improve the farming
conditions, transport and other infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
In his inspection, Zou pointed out that township enterprises,
which may do processing of farm and sideline produce,
constitute an important component of the rural economy.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he urged local officials to carry out the central
government policies about the reform of state-owned enterprises.
</P>
