<HEADLINE> US Reaffirms Its Commitment to Saudi Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The United States Defense
Minister William Cohen today reaffirmed the US commitment to the
security of Saudi Arabia, reports reaching here from Saudi red-sea
coast city of Jeddah said.
</P>
<P>
Cohen made the remarks before he wrapped up his two-day visit
to the world top oil producer and exporter. He held talks with
Saudi King Fahd Bin Abdul Aziz and his Saudi counterpart Prince
Sultan Bin Abdul Aziz last night.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said his talks with Saudi leaders also tackled means of
boosting security and stability in the Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
Cohen called on Iran to change its positions towards Saudi
Arabia through deeds, noting Iran's desire to improve its
relations with Saudi Arabia following the victory of moderate
Mohammed Khatami in Iranian presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
He said Washington was "hopeful but skeptical" on Iran and
"for the time being our policy is going to remain constant."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Saudi Prince Sultan denied Cohen's visit was aimed
at "resolving disputes between both countries" on the
investigation of the truck blast at the Khobar military housing
complex in Dhahran on June 25 last year that killed 19 U.S. airmen.
</P>
<P>
Cohen also reportedly brushed aside that the Federal Bureau of
Investigation lodged complaints over the Saudi security
authorities' non-cooperation due to what reports said Washington
and Riyadh were at odds over the investigation.
</P>
<P>
U.S. relations with Saudis have at times been strained in
the past year over Saudi handling of the investigation of
the car bomb.
</P>
<P>
So far the evidence is still inconclusive and the
investigation continues, Cohen reportedly said aboard his
plane en route to Saudi Arabia Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Prince Sultan also said his country hoped the U.S.
"should back the Oslo, Madrid and Washington peace accords" on
the Middle East process.
</P>
<P>
Cohen will arrive in Kuwait later today to continue his
Gulf tour. Official sources said Cohen's talks with Kuwait
leaders would focus on military cooperation and the situation
in Southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait deputy Prime Minister and Defense Minister Sheikh Salem
Sabah Al-Salem Al-Sabah said Saturday that Cohen's visit came
within the framework of bolstering the Kuwaiti-U.S. ties and
common understanding in the defense field. 
</P>
</TEXT>
