<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-15 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli High Court Rules Against Indicting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu survived another legal challenge today as Israeli High
Court of Justice rejected petitions to indict him for his role in
a corruption scandal.
</P>
<P>
The five-judge panel ruled with a vote of 4-1 against
overturning the decision made by Attorney General Elyakim
Rubinstein and State Attorney Edana Arbel, who rejected the
police recommendation of indicting Netanyahu and Justice Minister
Tzahi Hanegbi for their roles in the Bar-On scandal.
</P>
<P>
The court said there was no reason to review the state
prosecution's decision not to indict Netanyahu and Hanegbi. It
claimed that it would not intervene in the decision unless it was
entirely unreasonable.
</P>
<P>
On April 20, Rubinstein and Arbel announced that they had no
sufficient evidence to indict Netanyahu and Hanegbi with fraud and
breach of trust in appointing former Jerusalem lawyer Roni Bar-On
as the attorney general.
</P>
<P>
The scandal, exposed in January by state television Channel I,
sparked a government crisis that threatened to topple Netanyahu
government.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu was suspected of making a deal with his political
ally Aryeh Deri, leader of the powerful Shas party, who allegedly
conditioned his party's support to the Hebron agreement on
Bar-On's appointment.
</P>
<P>
By getting Bar-On appointed, Deri hoped to gain a favorable
plea-bargain deal in his bribery trial. The state prosecution
decided to indict only Deri with fraud and breach of trust for
pushing for Bar-On's appointment.
</P>
<P>
Following the state prosecution's announcement not to indict
Netanyahu and Hanegbi, the opposition Meretz leader Yossi Sarid
and Labor lawmaker Yossi Sarid filed two separate petitions
against the decision.
</P>
<P>
The civilian watchdog organization The Movement for Quality
Government also submitted a petition demanding remove Hanegbi
from his office "for failing to act according to accepted norms"
of public behavior. Hanegbi reportedly gave false information to
cabinet ministers on Bar-On's qualification in order to get
Bar-On's appointment.
</P>
<P>
The petition was also rejected by the high court. Moreover, the
court upheld the state prosecution's decision not to publish the
recommendation by the police investigative team calling for
indictments all round.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's office immediately welcomed the high court ruling,
saying "justice has been done."
</P>
<P>
While conceding their defeat in the legal battle to bring down
Netanyahu government over the Bar-On scandal, opposition lawmakers
vowed to continue challenging Netanyahu in the public arena.
</P>
<P>
"It's not the end. It's a turning point in the whole
affair. And it's beginning of the end of Netanyahu's term in
government as the prime minister," said Yossi Beilin, a former
minister in the Labour government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
