<HEADLINE> Premier Li Peng Completes Inspection Tour in Sichuan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, June 15 (Xinhua) -- During an inspection tour from
June 11 to 14 in southwest China's Sichuan Province, Premier Li
Peng showed great concern for a gigantic hydraulic power project,
the reform of state-owned enterprises and poverty relief work.
</P>
<P>
On June 12, Li went to the construction site of the Ertan
Hydraulic Power Station, a major stop in his inspection. He had
proposed the construction of the station in 1982 when he was
a vice-minister of the then Ministry of Water Resources and
Electric Power.
</P>
<P>
Being the biggest hydraulic power project in China by the end
of the century, the Ertan station will play a decisive role in
boosting economic growth in Sichuan Province and Chongqing
Municipality, and southwest China as a whole.
</P>
<P>
The station has been under construction for six years, its
total installed capacity will be 3.3 million kw. It is expected
that the first group of 550,000-kw water turbo-generators will go
into operation in July next year.
</P>
<P>
The premier was pleased to learn the smooth progress of the
station's construction and affirmed the way of competitive
international bidding to raise funds and seek loans for the huge
power project.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, he noted that the saving on water should be
given the same importance as the exploitation of water resources.
</P>
<P>
During his inspection, Li urged local officials to actively
explore the way of revitalizing state enterprises in line with the
requirements of the socialist market economy, adding that advanced
technology and strict management measures have proved successful
in bringing about the success of enterprises.
</P>
<P>
As to the fact that more than four million people in Sichuan
are living in poverty, the premier pointed out that to increase
local people's scientific knowledge and raise their educational
quality are key to changing the backward outlook in impoverished
areas.
</P>
<P>
On the basis of local resources, the areas must develop crop
planting, poultry raising and other undertakings to improve
economic returns and raise farmers' income, Li said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
