<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Says Its Unemployment Rate Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Iran said it has reduced the
unemployment rate from 11.9 percent eight years ago to 9.1 percent
at present.
</P>
<P>
According to a local press report today, Karamali Ahmadi,
Director of the Fund for Supporting Employment Opportunities
(FSEO), said that the figure will further drop to 9 percent by the
end of the Second Five-Year Development Plan (1995-1999).
</P>
<P>
Ahmadi was quoted by the Persian daily Salam as saying that
some 40 million U.S. dollars was allocated by the government for
establishing training centers for the jobless.
</P>
<P>
He added that this year some 45,000 people would be trained in
450 centers across Iran; his organization has allocated some 6.3
million dollars this year in self-employment loans to a total of
5,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Specialists noted that the highly fluid nature of Iran's labor
market and the large size of the informal service sector makes
relatively accurate estimates of employment levels impossible.
</P>
<P>
They noted that the official unemployment rate of 9.1 percent
is far too low, since the younger generation born after the 1979
Islamic revolution, which accounts for almost half the population,
now began to join the labor force.
</P>
<P>
Private estimates put the unemployment rate at 25 percent, but
the Business Monitor International believes a rough estimate is
round 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
Foreign diplomats in Tehran suggest that the country's
unemployment rate is rising, rather than declining, and this trend
will continue in the short-to-medium term as population growth
outstrips job creation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
