<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Paintings of Qi Baishi, His Daughter, Granddaughter on Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 15 (Xinhua) -- A paintings show of Qi Baishi
(1863-1957), one of China's most famed painter in modern history,
and of his daughter and granddaughter, today opened here in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition was dedicated to greet Hong Kong's return to the
motherland and mark the 40th anniversary of the death of Qi
Baishi.
</P>
<P>
On show are 120 paintings, 18 of which were painted by Qi
Baishi, which are from a cultural museum in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Qi Baishi was famous for his outstanding successes in
traditional Chinese painting, signets, poets and calligraph
accounted in thousands.
</P>
<P>
Qi, once served as chairman of Chinese Artists' Association, was
best known for drawing shrimps. Shrimps under Qi's painting pen
were in simple style and single color but lifelike.
</P>
<P>
Qi Liangzhi, 67, the youngest daughter of Qi, was also skilled
in painting fish, shrimps, flowers, birds, mountains, rivers and
fruits. Qi Yuanyuan, 34, daughter of Qi Liangzhi, was good at figure
painting as well as animals and flowers.
</P>
<P>
Qi's students, Xu Lin and Lou Shibai, attended today's opening
ceremony of the week-long show.  
</P>
</TEXT>
