<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clan Attack Kills 10 in Somali Port City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, June 15 (Xinhua) -- At least 10 people were killed
and about 15 others wounded when armed men attacked stores and
restaurants in Somalia's southern port town of Kismayu last
night, a local radio said.
</P>
<P>
According to the commercial VHF radio from Kismaio, 500 km
south of the capital, the attack was carried out by more than 50
armed men belonging to the Marehan clan of the former dictator
Mohamed Siad Barre who fired indiscriminately upon people
enjoying tea at about 9:15 local time last night.
</P>
<P>
The attack was said to be a continuation of the previous
conflict over the control of Kismaio between Marehan and Majerten
clansmen.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the Marehans were taking revenge over
those of Majerten militiamen who dominate the town.
</P>
<P>
The Marehan militiamen have come from Gobwein village, north
of Kismaio, and sneaked through the defensive positions of the
Majerten clansmen outside the city.
</P>
<P>
All streets were deserted and business centers were closed
down as a result of the attack.
</P>
<P>
The Marehans have deserted the town of Kismaio after last
night's incident and retreated back to Gobwein village.
</P>
<P>
The Marehan clansmen were driven out of Kismaio early in the
year following the Majertens suspicion that they aligned
themselves with the government of Hussein Mohamed Aidid.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, thousands of people demonstrated in Mogadishu
Stadium today, in commemoration of the second anniversary of the
government established by late general Mohamed Farah Aidid.
</P>
<P>
Hussein Mohamed Aidid and his senior officials in their
government also attended the demonstration.
</P>
<P>
Aidid has called the Ethiopian forces to withdraw
unconditionally from Somalia's soil, ''the Ethiopian action is
intolerable in regard to the territorial integrity of Somalia,''
said Aidid.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian forces still maintain their control over the
towns of Bulo Hawo and Luq which they have invaded Thursday in
their third military incursion into Somalia since last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
