<HEADLINE> Guangdong, Hong Kong Youth Burn Drug in Humen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Over 1,000 young people from
south China's Guangdong province and Hong Kong burned up 150
kilograms of heroin and "ice" drug today in the very pool where
China's national hero Lin Zexu ordered to burn opium seized from
foreign traders 158 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The activity, designed to greet Hong Kong's return to the
motherland, was sponsored by Guangdong Narcotics Control
Committee, Guangdong Youth Federation, and a special preparatory
committee of Hong Kong young people for the celebration of Hong
Kong's return to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Over 800 young people from Hong Kong made a special trip to
attend the activity held in Humen county, known for "Opium-Burning
in Humen" in history.
</P>
<P>
158 years ago, Lin Zexu, an imperial envoy, was sent to look
into the problem of opium trafficking. Over 20,000 cases of opium
with a total weight of 1.15 million kg, were seized from British
and American traders and were all burned up at once in Humen, on
June 3, 1839.
</P>
<P>
Young participants also signed their names on a banner with a
map of China as the background to swear they would always remember
the history of "Opium-Burning in Humen" and create a bright
future. The banner with signatures of 1,997 Guangdong and Hong
Kong youth would be on display on July 6 in Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
