<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Declaration of D-8 Summit Issued in Istanbul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISTANBUL, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from the eight
Group Muslim countries, known as Developing-8 (D-8), signed a
declaration here today to officially announce the establishment of
the bloc.
</P>
<P>
Presidents, prime ministers as well as other senior officials
from Turkey, Egypt, Pakistan, Indonesia, Nigeria, Bangladesh,
Malaysia and Iran attended the one-day D-8 Group summit in
Istanbul, the largest city of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The declaration issued at the meeting said that the D-8 group
decided to establish a mechanism for developing cooperation.
</P>
<P>
It added said that the D-8 Group will be a forum with no
adverse effect the member states' commitments to other
international or regional organizations.
</P>
<P>
The document noted that the main objective of the D-8 Group is
to boost social and economic development of its member states in
accordance in accordance with the principle of peace, dialog,
cooperation, justice, equality and democracy.
</P>
<P>
The declaration stated that the cooperation among the eight
Muslim countries will encompass all areas, including political
consultation and coordination-ordination at the international
stage.
</P>
<P>
The summit approved a report of the council which agreed
on six major projects to be launched immediately, said the
declaration, but no details on the projects were available.
</P>
<P>
The D-8 Group will be a global forum whose membership is open
to other developing countries, said the declaration, adding the
group is determined to cooperate with both the developing and
developed countries in realization of its goals.
</P>
<P>
The declaration added that an appropriate mechanism will be
worked out to liaise with other relevant international
organizations, particularly with the Organization of Islamic
Countries.
</P>
<P>
According to the document, an executive director is to be
appointed to provide coordination among the eight member states.
</P>
<P>
It was decided at the meeting that the second D-8 Group summit
meeting will be held in Dhaka, capital of Bangladesh, at the end
of 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970615.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-15 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Rejects US Decision to Remove </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia has expressed
full rejection to the U.S. Congress' decision to move the
U.S. embassy in Israel from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem, saying it's an
actual consideration of the disputed city as Israel's capital.
</P>
<P>
This was expressed by Saudi Second Deputy Prime Minister and
Defense Minister Prince Sultan ibn Abdul-Aziz during his talks
with the visiting U.S. Defense Minister William Cohen in the Saudi
port city of Jeddah last night, according to the Kuwait News
Agency today.
</P>
<P>
Prince Sultan said "Saudi Arabia will be glad to hear the
U.S. leaders' opposition to this decision."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Congress issued a resolution last Wednesday to
recognize Jerusalem as the undivided capital of Israel and
allocate 100 million U.S. dollars to move the U.S. embassy in Tel
Aviv to the controversial city.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made amid strong international criticism and
Arab condemnation.
</P>
<P>
The hardline policy of the Jewish state has again plunged the
Middle East peace process into deadlock since mid-march, due to
its construction of a new Jewish settlement in East Jerusalem it
seized from the Arabs in the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
The Israelis have claimed Jerusalem as the inseparable capital
of the country while the Palestinians want to make it as the
capital city of their independent state in the future.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the Kuwait National Assembly also
condemned, in a statement Saturday, the U.S. congress' decision
and requested U.S. President Bill Clinton to overturn the decision.
</P>
<P>
The national assembly expressed grave concern over the
decision which it said would lead the region to "a turmoil of
violence."
</P>
<P>
It said the Kuwaiti parliament hoped the Clinton
Administration would be able to overturn the congress decision,
especially under the current circumstances, as a sign of respect
for Muslims around the world.
</P>
<P>
It described the decision as "a blow to the peace efforts in
the region and a declaration of war against the Palestinians who
would not accept any peace depriving them of their legitimate
rights."
</P>
<P>
The statement said the congress decision would undermine the
international and U.S. efforts to save the peace process from
the setback it suffered due to Israel's stubborn policy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
