<HEADLINE> Expansion Starts on Northwest Chinese Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Zou Jiahua
attended an inauguration ceremony today for expansion on
Zhongchuan airport in Lanzhou, capital of northwest China's Gansu
Province.
</P>
<P>
Total investment for the project will reach 1.23 billion yuan,
involving the fourth batch of loans, totaling 6.3 billion Japanese
yen, from Japan's Overseas Cooperative Fund. Work will be
completed in four years.
</P>
<P>
The project, approved by the State Council, has been listed as
a key basic construction project by the State Planning
Commission. The airport will be expanded in line with its required
passenger handling capacity in the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
The expansion project includes a 3,600-m-long runway with
4D-category standard, a parallel slideway and four roads for
liaison purpose, as well as parking aprons for 16 more airplanes,
and a terminal with a floor space of 25,000 sq m.
</P>
<P>
Other necessary facilities, in terms of pilot, meteorology, the
supply of oil, water, and electricity, will also be built, airport
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Zhongchuan airport plays an important role in the country's
airport and air route layout. Built in 1968, however, it cannot
accommodate large aircrafts because of its low technological
standard.
</P>
<P>
In order to meet the demands of an ever increasing cargo and
passengers, the airport has to be upgraded, authorities say.
</P>
</TEXT>
