<HEADLINE> Enhanced Cooperation Called for in D-8 Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISTANBUL, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel called, at the ongoing D-8 summit today, on the Muslim
member countries to strengthen their cooperation in a bid to play
a bigger and more energetic role next century.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the summit of the D-8 Group summit in Turkey's
largest city of Istanbul, Demirel said that the D-8 Group, namely
Turkey, Iran, Egypt, Nigeria, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Malaysia and
Indonesia, should make use of what he called the new mechanism to
boost bilateral and multilateral cooperation in various sectors
among all the countries in the world.
</P>
<P>
He noted that an increasingly interdependent world urges the
D-8 member countries to join forces to overcome their
difficulties faced with their economic development.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the participants at the meeting, Turkish Prime
Minister Necmettin Erbakan stressed that the eight Muslim
countries should further cooperate for the benefit of their
peoples.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan claimed that the formation of the D-8 Group is aimed
at helping their member countries play " a productive role"
instead of competing with the Western states in the
international affairs.
</P>
<P>
At the summit, Iranian President Hashemi Rafsanjani said that
the D-8 Group opens "new dimensions for cooperation among Muslim
countries," describing the creation of the Muslim group as "a
particularly important event."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the D-8 Group member countries have
considerable potentials in enhancing their economic and
technical cooperation in various fields.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of his president Hosni Mubarak who did not attend the
meeting, Egyptian Prime Minister al-Ganzouri said that his country
has positively responded to the establishment of the group, adding
its structure would provide a distinct forum for cooperation at
different levels.
</P>
<P>
In his speech made at the meeting, Indonesian President
Suharto called for close coordination among the eight Muslim
countries to make the D-8 group's mechanism work smoothly.
</P>
<P>
Suharto appealed to the group to attach great importance to
their cooperation in private sectors, noting "the contributions
of our private business sectors will be crucial in the fight
against poverty."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the summit, Pakistani Prime Minister Mian Nawaz
Sharif explained in details the six principles adopted at the
summit, "peace instead of conflict, dialog instead of
confrontation, cooperation instead of exploitation, justice
instead of double standards, equality instead of discrimination
and democracy instead of oppression."
</P>
<P>
Noting that stability and economic development is closely
linked, Sharif urged the D-8 Group member states to spare no
efforts to work more for the benefit of their people.
</P>
<P>
Describing the Istanbul summit as "a historic meeting,"
Bangladesh Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina said that the D-8 group
should play a substantive role in promoting cooperation among its
member states as they share deep-rooted historical, religious,
cultural affinities and abundance of human and natural resources
within the bloc.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the Bangladesh leader called on the D-8 group states
to make special efforts for enhanced cooperation with the seven
major industrialized countries, known as G-7 Group comprising the
United States, Britain, France, Germany, Canada, Italy and
Japan.
</P>
<P>
At the Istanbul summit, the formation of the D-8 Group was
officially announced, and some presidents, prime ministers and
senior leaders from the eight member states attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The D-8 Group was launched by Turkey late last year, and its
first foreign ministerial meeting was convened in Istanbul early
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
