<DOCNO> XIE19970615.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fierce Media Battle to Unfold Around HK's Handover (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 15 (Xinhua) --The opening of a 9,000-sq. m
press center here today raised the curtain on a media battle of
the century, in which more than 8,000 journalists from all over
the world will exert themselves in the coverage of Hong Kong's
historic return to China.
</P>
<P>
Calling it "the media battle in the century" is by no means an
exaggeration now that over 770 media organizations deploy their
best contingents equipped with state-of-the-art equipment to
capture the historic moment at midnight June 30, when China
resumes its exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Many journalists described the handover as a historic event
that happens only once in history and only once in one's lifetime.
</P>
<P>
"You can't afford not to be there," said a corespondent of CNN
International, which sends an additional staff of 50 to join the
16 residential journalists in Hong Kong. The total number of
American applicants for the coverage hits 1,030, trailing Hong
Kong with 2,755 and Japan with 1,319.
</P>
<P>
All the three major television networks in the United States
-- ABC, CBS and NBC -- are dispatching strong contingents to Hong
Kong together with top newscasters on the scene. Three leading
American anchors -- Peter Jennings for ABC, Dan Rather for CBS and
Tom Brokaw for NBC -- will all fly in to air their regular
half-hour nightly news broadcasts from the newly-established
Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
A large corps of 1,319 journalists are coming in from Japan,
including all leading television networks -- NHK, Fuji TV, TV
Asahi, TBS, NTV and TV Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
NHK, the oldest broadcasting corporation in Japan, will enhance
its presence in Hong Kong by forming a 50-member special coverage
pool and bringing in a set of advanced equipment called
Communications Satellite Portable (CSP), which can transmit
signals directly from the ground to the satellite.
</P>
<P>
Ryuichiro Nakamura, NHK Hong Kong Bureau chief, said: "The 21st
century is the era of China. The return of Hong Kong to China will
enhance China's position in the Asia-Pacific region, both
politically and economically." He believed that the devising of
"one country, two systems" is a "unique and practical way" to
maintain Hong Kong's vitality.
</P>
<P>
CCTV, China's national television network, will have a record
number of 289 reporters, newscasters, cameramen and technicians on
the scene -- a strong battalion equipped with helicopters and
DSNG, a mobile satellite TV station.
</P>
<P>
"We will give a live, 72-hour blanket coverage of the event.
For the Chinese nation, it is a moment to wash off the 150-year
humiliation and shame," said Li Liansheng, deputy chief of CCTV,
who has started to command at the forefront -- CCTV working booths
at the Press and Broadcasting Center.
</P>
<P>
The center provides some 600 free seats for news writers, and
more than 230 working booths which have all been booked well
before its opening today.
</P>
<P>
The handover ceremony is doubtless the center of attention for
all TV networks. At the stroke of midnight local time, all eyes
will be riveted on TV screens -- the lowering of the Jack Union
and the raising of the Five-Star Red Flag.
</P>
<P>
The final lap of transition is where the dominant battlefield
lies, and where every TV producer competes fiercely for speed and
accuracy to attract its audience. Many TV networks will start from
June 23 to mount a week-long or ten-day program focusing on
various aspects of the handover.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970615.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fierce Media Battle to Unfold Around HK's Handover (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CNBC, a service launched by the Asian subsidiary of NBC,
announced that its live, blanket coverage would be spliced with
in-depth analysis and interviews with prominent figures. Names of
these interviewees are still kept in secret at this moment since
"it is our edge", as a CNBC spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
For cameramen, taking a good shooting position is gaining an
advantage in the game. CNBC has rented three rooms on top of the
Regent Hotel, which commands spectacular views across the Victoria
Harbor to the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Center
Extension, the official venue of the handover ceremony.
</P>
<P>
NHK also has obtained a good filming place, which commands a
good view of both the handover site and Tamar, where Britain will
hold the farewell ceremony, according to its bureau chief.
</P>
<P>
Competition is keen not only among television producers, but
also among news agencies, newspapers and magazines. A veteran
journalist in Hong Kong called the coverage of the handover "a
world-class news writing competition".
</P>
<P>
Reuters will bring in seven extra reporters to strengthen its
20-member residential team, AFP will double its group to 16
correspondents, and AP will boost its contingent to 80, who will
belong to four divisions of news, photo, audio and TV.
</P>
<P>
"The return of Hong Kong to China is a vital part of China's
growth and development," said Rodney Pinder, Reuters Asia news
editor.
</P>
<P>
"Economically, it's a huge and immensely important story,"
according to Pinder, who believed that the importance of China is
the no.1 reason that turns Hong Kong into a global focus.
</P>
<P>
Fok Yit Wye, a reporter from Singapore daily Lianhe Zaobao,
said: "The handover is important for the whole of Asian people,
because it is the end of colonial rule in the region, something
they or their ancestors have experienced over the past century."
</P>
<P>
Economic relationship is also a factor affecting Asian people's
feelings toward the handover, she said. Many Asian countries have
strong economic interests in Hong Kong and they reasonably want to
see a smooth and successful handover.
</P>
<P>
Chief Editor of AFP Hong Kong Bureau Richard Ingham said that
there has never been an event like this in history. It is the
first time that a piece of land is transferred from one country to
another in a peaceful and negotiated way rather than resorting to
arms.
</P>
<P>
The big event is unfolding in two weeks' time and the entire
world is watching.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
