<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Production in Nigeria Faces Setback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Oil production in Nigeria, the
African oil giant, might suffer a setback as its leading
multinational partners in the oil industry are threatening to
shut down operations.
</P>
<P>
According to industry sources, Shell, Mobil, Chevron, Elf and
Agip, all major foreign oil companies in Nigeria, are considering
shutting down oil operations for some 30 days to forestall
financial crisis with the 40 percent budget cut by the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian authorities approved in the 1997 budget the sum
of 2.05 billion U.S. dollars for cash-call payments, which is
down from estimated 3.5 billion dollars for the joint venture
partner operations between the Nigerian National Petroleum
Corporation and the foreign firms.
</P>
<P>
The foreign partners have appealed for re-consideration by the
government, but half way into the year, they saw no sign of a
government review of the budget to maintain the current levels of
crude oil production.
</P>
<P>
Worse still, given the 40 percent cut, the payment by
government did not commence until April. Before then the high
interest from the funds the oil companies borrowed made them "all
losers on all fronts," according to an oil company official, who
described the situation as "rather disappointing".
</P>
<P>
Most of the leading oil companies, industry sources said, have
started giving back leased rigs which are used in oil drilling,
apparently because the machines have become idle for lack of
funds so as to reduce the cost for hiring them.
</P>
<P>
At least four rigs, two hired by Shell and two by Mobil, have
left Nigeria and more are expected to leave, they said.
</P>
<P>
Shell alone produces about one million barrels per day, almost
half of Nigeria's daily production of 2.3 barrels. Mobil also
takes a rather big share of the daily output.
</P>
<P>
Analysts noted the withdrawal of rigs will necessarily
increase the expense to re-hire them if and when the situation
becomes more conducive for the Nigerian operators, resulting in a
shoot up of oil production cost. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970615.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Small City Taps Market with Small Commodities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Years ago, only a few Chinese
could point out-of-towners in the direction of Yiwu, a remote city
in the central part of East China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Now, the 27,000-stall China Small Commodity Market in the city
is a well-known destination for traders and shoppers seeking to
buy bunches of goods and test their bargaining skills.
</P>
<P>
"The transaction volume in the market hit more than 20 billion
yuan (approx. 1.5 billion US dollars) last year, the largest among
100,000-odd trade fairs in China," said Li Zizhou, deputy general
manager of China Small Commodity Holding Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that about 200,000 people from home and abroad
trade at the fair everyday. So far this year, more than 1,000
businesspeople from 20-plus countries and regions, including
neighboring southeast Asian nations and Latin America, bought
goods here, Lin said.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 20 years ago, when China's economy switched from the
rigid centralized planning system to a market-oriented mode, Yiwu
needed a new means of connecting with the outside business world.
</P>
<P>
Like other counties and small cities in south and east China,
Yiwu had no natural resources, limited farmland and increasing
numbers of surplus laborers in the rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The local government created a plan in the mid-1980s to build a
commercial hub from scratch. It started out with a free market,
where only poor-quality products were sold, accompanied by the
strong local dialects of the peddlers.
</P>
<P>
Now, the market has 28 categories of commodities with more than
30,000 varieties, all of which give a powerful boost to the local
economy.
</P>
<P>
"The commodity circulation gave impetus to the overall
development of the small city, in particular its tertiary sectors,
such as finance, transport, real estate, catering and
warehousing," said Yiwu's mayor Wei Chaoran.
</P>
<P>
Wei said Yiwu has been regarded as one of the fastest-growing
cities at the county level in China. "The per-capita income of
farmers last year reached 4,200 yuan, or ten times the figure of
ten years ago. Both the per-capita gross domestic product and
savings deposits ranked first in similar administrative localities
in Zhejiang," he said.
</P>
<P>
The speedy development in the city even caught the attention of
Chinese economists who dubbed it the "Yiwu Phenomenon."
</P>
<P>
"Yiwu has set an example for activating the economy at the
county level by building up a local commodity circulation system
that caters to the market economy," said noted economist Gao
Shangquan.
</P>
<P>
The market is now not only renowned in China, but is also
considered a springboard for foreign manufacturers seeking to
enter the vast Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
Margo Robinson, business planning director of Eastman Kodak
Co., recently toured the market to learn about film sales. "It is
incredible that a small city now runs such a big market," she told
Lin.
</P>
<P>
Years ago, Toshiba Corporation of Japan only set up regional
sales branches for its batteries in China's provincial
capitals. Now Yiwu has become its general agent in all of east
China, thanks to the reputation of the market. Sales of Toshiba
batteries in Yiwu are estimated to exceed 30 million yuan this
year.
</P>
<P>
Guests from Japan, Russia and Brazil have even suggested that
the market operators set up shops in their countries. "We're
considering the possibility," Lin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
