<HEADLINE> Nigerian Universities Told to Cut Recruitments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian universities have been
instructed to cut their recruiments for the current academic year by as
much as 40 percent, the Sunday Tribune reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the National Universities Commission which
gave the instruction did not give the reason, but the biting
financial difficulties inflicting Nigerian universities might
account for the cut in recuitment.
</P>
<P>
It will be the third straight year that universities cut their
recruitments, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In the 1995/1996 academic year, about 82,179 candidates were
admitted into universities, out of about 415,000 applicants.
</P>
<P>
On May 24 this year, about 360,000 students sat for the
national Joint Matriculation Examinations, the newspaper said.
</P>
</TEXT>
