<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-15 09:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Summit of D-8 Group Opens in Istanbul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Istanbul, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel today called on the eight Muslim developing countries,
known as D-8 Group, to strengthen their cooperation and to
play a more energetic role in the next century.
</P>
<P>
Opening the D-8 Group summit meeting in Turkey's largest
city of Istanbul, Demirel said that the D-8 countries should
make use of the new mechanism to boost bilateral and
multilateral cooperation in various sectors among all the
countries in the world.
</P>
<P>
He noted that an increasingly interdependent world urges the
D-8 Group member countries to make joint efforts to overcome
their difficulties they are facing in economic development.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the participants in the meeting, Turkish Prime
Minister Necmettin Erbakan said that the group will make further
cooperation among the eight Muslim countries for the benefits of
their people.
</P>
<P>
He said that the formation of the D-8 Group is aimed at
helping their member countries play " a productive role" in the
international affairs.
</P>
<P>
Iranian President Hashemi Rafsanjani, Egyptian Prime Minister
Ganzouri, Indonesian President Suharto, Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif and other leaders of the D-8 nations also spoke at
the meeting, calling on the D-8 Group to make special efforts for
enhanced cooperation with the seven major industrial countries,
known as G-7.
</P>
<P>
The Istanbul summit, which officially announced the formation
of the D-8 Group, has attracted presidents, prime ministers as
well as senior officials from the eight member states including
Turkey, Iran, Egypt, Nigeria, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Malaysia and
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak failed to turn out at the
first D-8 Group summit, making the host state disappointed.
</P>
<P>
A veteran Egyptian diplomat, who is close to the Egyptian
delegation headed by the Egyptian prime minister, told Xinhua
earlier that Mubarak's move could be seen as a protest against
Turkey's massive military incursion in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The D-8 Group was launched by Turkey's Islamic Prime
Minister Necmettin Erbakan late last year, and convened its
first foreign ministerial meeting in Istanbul early this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
