<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-15 08:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Official Denies Military Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISTANBUL, June 15 (Xinhua) -- A Turkish high-ranking official
today denied the reports that Turkey has begun to withdraw its
troops from northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry Spokesman Omer Akbel told Xinhua that
the return of some government troops to Turkey is "a garrison
relief", adding that it is only a routine move of the military.
</P>
<P>
Rejecting latest media reports concerning the alleged Turkey's
withdrawal from northern Iraq, Akbel said that the Turkish
government has no such a plan at the moment.
</P>
<P>
Some 50,000-strong Turkish troops began a cross-border military
operation on May, 14 in northern Iraq to attack the outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), which has fought a 13-year
separatist war in southeast Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's large-scale military operation to wipe out the PKK
rebels has become a sensitive subject of the Istanbul summit of
eight Muslim developing countries bloc, known as D-8 group, consisting of
Egypt, Turkey, Iran, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Nigeria, Malaysia and
Indonesia. The summit opens today.
</P>
<P>
In a Saturday meeting with his Turkish counterpart Necmettin
Erbakan, Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri urged Turkey to
end its military incursion as early as possible.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan, however, said that Turkey's military action is aimed
at sweeping PKK out of this region, stressing that the Turkish
government troops launched the campaign at the request of the
Iraqi Kurdistan Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
Tukey's military operation in northern Iraq has drawn sharp
criticism from the Arab world and some Western countries as well.
</P>
<P>
Local reports has said that Turkey has begun to pull part of
its troops out of the region as a gesture to appease some D-8
member states which are opposed to the Turkey's military
incursion in northern Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
