<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Reiterates Decision to Restructure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 15 (Xinhua) --Tanzanian President Benjamin
Mkapa Friday reiterated the government's decision to restructure
the National Bank of Commerce (NBC) despite public outcry to stop
the move, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The president said this during a meeting with the Director of
the World Bank, Jim Adams, assuring him that his country
remains committed to economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said that the doors were wide open for foreign investors
in a bid to strengthen the operations of the largest banking firm
in the country.
</P>
<P>
He said the government cannot bolster NBC any more, because
the government can not pump tax payers' money to back the bank up
as it did before.
</P>
<P>
The president said the past trend cannot be sustained because
the funds initially provided to NBC would now be channelled to
improving social services for the benefit of the people.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa assured the World Bank director that the restructuring
process would be warily implemented, adding that national
interest would be a priority during the exercise.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank director agreed with the president, saying that
the bank reform should ensure provision of banking services in
the rural areas where the majority lived.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, addressing commanders of the Tanzania People's
Defense Forces (TPDF) last Wednesday, President Mkapa said that
the idea to restructure NBC was first recommended by the
Nyirabu Commission in 1990.
</P>
<P>
However, the bank has been limping financially since then,
forcing the government to pump in funds to sustain it.
</P>
<P>
When restructured, the NBC will be divided into three
subsidiary banks - trade, regional and micro-finance banks - each
serving different customer groups, according to the president.
</P>
</TEXT>
