<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Tries to Fill Up U.S. Sugar Quota </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
today authorized the Department of Agriculture to export 27,000
tons of sugar to the United States to fill up the additional U.S.
quota for this crop year, and import the same amount for domestic
consumption.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement, the presidential office said Ramos
"authorized the Department of Agriculture, through the National
Food authority (NFA), to fill up the additional United States
sugar quota of about 27,000 metric tons for the fourth quarter of
crop year 1996-1997."
</P>
<P>
Ramos directed the Department of Finance and other concerned
agencies to grant the NFA tariff-free privileges for the
importation of an equivalent volume of sugar, the office said.
</P>
<P>
The NFA or its assigned agents will export some 27,000 tons of
qualified domestically produced "B" sugar held as domestic stocks
to the United States before September 30, 1997, it said.
</P>
<P>
And the NFA or its assigned agent will import sugar from the
world market through a countertrade arrangement to satisfy
domestic market requirements.
</P>
<P>
U.S. embassy officials has said that if Manila fails to fill up
the U.S. quota this year, Washington will cancel the quota and
import sugar from other countries.
</P>
<P>
Since the Philippines opened its sugar market several years
ago, large amounts of imported sugar have poured into the country
with prices much lower than the local product. The Philippine
sugar industry has been seriously undermined by imported sugar and
could hardly meet export demands.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
