<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Car Simulators Introduced in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Car simulators are now being
adapted in Israel to teach drivers without denting bumpers or
endangering others on the road.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of the Jerusalem Post today, classes
using a driving simulator will be held in Jerusalem within the
coming months.
</P>
<P>
Eli Cohen, an entrepreneur and owner of a towing company in
Jerusalem, received a loan from the Jerusalem Center for Business
Initiatives to open the preventive-driving course project.
</P>
<P>
The simulator has a chair that looks like a driver's seat, a
steering wheel, brakes and other instruments.
</P>
<P>
The advantage of a simulator, Cohen said, was that it tests the
driver's reaction time to various situations on the road.
</P>
<P>
The computerized device also tests the driver's ability to
carry out difficult tasks, such as slowing down on a highway to
park on the soft shoulders, driving on a slippery highway or
coping with inclement weather.
</P>
<P>
If the driver is involved in an "accident," the sequence can be
screened over and over so he can learn from his mistakes.
</P>
<P>
Cohen, who has witnesses the results of bad driving as a
towing company owner, noted that the technique is useful not only
for teaching and testing driving learners, but also to teach
licensed drivers to hone their skills. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
