<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Bank, Cathay Pacific Sorry on Whale Meat Ads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Bank and Cathay
Pacific Airways Ltd. have admitted they were wrong to promote
whale-eating in advertising holidays to Japan, according to local
English-language newspaper South China Morning Post here today.
</P>
<P>
The joint Hong Kong Bank-Cathay Pacific promotion for credit
card holders - "All-Inclusive Fun in the Land of Rising Sun" -
told potential customers that local attractions included "Osaka
style cuisine such as sushi and whales."
</P>
<P>
Conservationists accused Cathay Pacific of hypocrisy for
promoting its green image while encouraging people to eat whales.
</P>
<P>
Whaling some species is permitted in Japan for research but
animal welfare campaigners say it is cruel to allow rare species
to end up in restaurants.
</P>
<P>
International Fund for Animal Welfare China director Jill
Robinson urged Hong Kong Bank and Cathay Pacific to retract the
words.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong Bank head of public affairs Michael Broadbent said
the company's usual checks and balances had failed.
</P>
<P>
"We just missed it. Obviously we are aware of the sensitivity
- it is a good old fashioned mistake," he said. "We apologize,"
he was quoted by the newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
Cathay Pacific spokesman Kwan Chuk-Fai said the "minor
oversight" was the result of copying a Japanese travel brochure.
</P>
<P>
"It is unfortunate and I hope it won't happen again. It is
definitely not the intention to promote people going to the city
for that purpose," said Charlie Stewart-Cox, a spokesman of the
Swire Group, of which Cathay Pacific is a member. 
</P>
</TEXT>
