<HEADLINE> Italy Says It Wins French Support on EU Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Italy said today it won support from
France in its drive to write key EU reforms into a revised
Maastricht Treaty due to be approved at the end of the two-day
Amsterdam Summit on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A French diplomat Hubert Vedrine had told the Italian Foreign
Minister Lamberto Dini that France backed Italy's efforts to
secure "substantive results, especially in the field of
institutional reform" in Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
The 15 EU leaders are expected to give final approval to a
revised draft of the Maastricht Treaty which was drawn up by the
Netherlands -- the country holding the rotating six-month EU
presidency -- and included some suggestions by Dini.
</P>
<P>
The draft proposed cutting the size of the EU commission to one
commissioner per country, reweighting votes to give bigger
countries more say and putting an end to veto rights by member
countries over EU policies.
</P>
<P>
Some member countries, notably Britain, opposed an end to veto
rights and small and large countries wrangled over the proposal
of reweighting votes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
