<HEADLINE> Brazil Not to Impose Embargo on Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian President
Fernando Henrique Cardoso said Friday his government will not
impose any embargo on Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso made the remarks while talking with visiting vice
president of Cuban Council of State Carlos Lage and Cuban
ambassador to Brazil Ramon Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Congress passed the notorious Helms-Burton law in
March, 1996, tightening the rein of embargo on Cuba. The law
requested the U.S. government to impose sanctions on foreign
companies investing in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The international community had strongly urged the U.S. to end
its three-decade-long embargo against Cuba, and to stop imposing
its laws on other countries.
</P>
<P>
Cardoso said the Brazilian government will insist on its
foreign policy of not imposing embargo on Cuba. 
</P>
