<HEADLINE> Yuan Hits Two-Year High Against Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 15 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese yuan hit a two-year
high against the US dollar twice in May on the Shanghai-based
national interbank foreign exchange market.
</P>
<P>
The renminbi surged to a 8.2913 high against the green-back on
May 27, the highest closing price since May 18, 1995 when the yuan
ended at 8.2892, today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The yuan has been rising slowly but continuously for more than
two years.
</P>
<P>
It closed at 8.2924 on May 30, slightly up from 8.2947 on May
5, the first trading day in May.
</P>
<P>
"The renminbi has been rising steadily for more than one year,
which is manily due to the substantial trade surplus and the surge
of foreign exchange reserves," a Bank of China dealer said.
</P>
<P>
China posted a 10.29 billion US dollars trade surplus in the
first four months of this year, a dramatic increase from 6.71
billion US dollars in the first three months.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign exchange reserve, however, stood at 115 billion
US dollars at the end of April.
</P>
<P>
Fewer interventions by the central bank also helped the yuan
soar to a two-year high.
</P>
<P>
Experts believe the yuan will continue its upward trend in the
near future because of the over-supply of dollars in the domestic
market.
</P>
<P>
The continued inflation decline strengthened the yuan, the
paper said. Statistics show that China's bench-mark retail price
inflation rose moderately by 0.8 percent year-on-year in
May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
