<HEADLINE> Sino-overseas Gold Mine Cooperative Project Going Ahead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 15 (Xinhua) -- A Sino-foreign gold mine
cooperative project is gaining progress, as two overseas investors
involved have been required to present their prefeasibility
reports by the China National Gold Corp (CNGC) before August 10.
</P>
<P>
The US-based Newmont and Australia-based Broken Hill
Proprietary Ltd Co. have long been interested in the Lannigou Gold
Mine cooperative project in southwestern Guizhou Province, today's
Business Weekly of China Daily quoted a CNGC official as saying.
</P>
<P>
China began in 1993 to open low-grade and metallurgically
refractory gold mines to foreign investment on a trial basis.
</P>
<P>
CNGC has provided the two companies with the geological
materials of the mine, whose main vein has a proven gold reserve
of about 60 tons.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign investors are also interested in a larger-scale
cooperation by exploring and exploiting the area surrounding the
mine. So CNGC provided them with all the geological materials
currently available of the surrounding area.
</P>
<P>
But the materials are far from enough for the investors to make
a decision to develop the project. And CNGC is looking forward to
further cooperation.
</P>
<P>
China produced 120 tons of gold last year, and gold production
is likely to approach 130 tons this year, said Ai Dacheng, deputy
director of the Gold Bureau's production section of the Ministry
of Metallurgical Industry.
</P>
<P>
This projected output will make China the fifth largest gold
producer in the world, Ai said. China came after South Africa, the
United States, Australia, Canada, and Russian last year in gold
production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
