<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's energy needs to reach three billion BEO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's needs for primary
energy will increase from 494 million barrels equivalent of oil
(BEO) at the start of the Second Long-Term Development Plan in
1994/95 to 3.0 billion BEO by 2018/19, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
"Such an increase is based on an assumption that during the
Second Long-Term Development Plan (from 1994 to 2019), Indonesia
will have an average of seven percent economic growth and 0.7
percent population growth," Mines and Energy Minister Ida Bagus
Sudjana said in Semarang, Central Java, on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
According reports reaching here today, Sudjana said that by
2018/19, the country's population will exceed the 250 million mark
and the country's per capita primary energy consumption is
expected to reach 11.8 BEO per annum.
</P>
<P>
"This means that primary energy consumption by 2019 will be
five-fold compared with that in 1994 which stood at 2.5 barrels
equivalent of oil," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that oil and natural gas remain the main suppliers of
the country's increasing energy needs.
</P>
<P>
He also said the country's consumption of oil fuels as sources
of energy has been steadily declining from 94.6 percent of primary
energy in 1970 to 73.5 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Despite declining in the percentage, the consumption of oil
fuels has been increasing in volume from 36 million BEO in 1970 to
271 million BEO in 1996, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Such a situation was mainly caused by the increasing economic
growth rate and higher people mobilization," Sudjana said.
</P>
<P>
He said the country's needs for oil fuels will continue to
increase in the future if Indonesia was unable to develop
alternative energy sources.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
