<HEADLINE> Thailand, Myanmar to Join Efforts to Curb Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and Myanmar are to
formulate common policies to curb the re-emergence and spread of
infectious diseases that are seriously affecting both countries.
</P>
<P>
Thai and Myanmar health officials will hold a meeting next
month to consider cross-border health problems, according to an
informed source here.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Thai provincial and central health officials
have reported the gradual spread of several diseases such as
malaria, tuberculosis, meningococcus meningitis, filariasis from
the Myanmar border area Thailand. Some of these illnesses had
been considered eradicated in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Organizers hope the meeting will come up with a concrete joint
plan for the prevention and elimination of these illnesses, the
source said.
</P>
<P>
The plan is likely to include the establishment of joint
networks, or committees, at the provincial level to do ground
work, the source said.  
