<HEADLINE> China's Land Freeze Hurts No Foreign-funded Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 15 (Xinhua) -- Foreign-funded projects won't be
affected by China's one-year land freeze on farmland requisitions
for non-agricultural purposes, today's China Daily quoted a land
administration official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Pan Mingcai, director of the construction land department of
the State Land Administration (SLA), said that overseas-backed
projects are encouraged to use idle land, such as unused land in
development zones.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investors are also encouraged to requisition wasteland
and shoaly land. And another way for them to get land is to
cooperate with Chinese companies who can invest their land in
cooperation, Pan said.
</P>
<P>
Projects that occupy farmland must get approval from the State
Council or wait for one year for the freeze to be lifted. "The
freeze is not to hold up construction projects but to promote
proper and efficient use of idle land," he said.
</P>
<P>
The freeze is expected to force non-agricultural construction
projects including foreign-funded ones to use other alternatives,
but won't apply to key State construction projects, and the
Comfortable Housing Project, which aims to ease housing
difficulties of urban families, the official said.
</P>
<P>
About 466,000 ha of farmland are occupied every year, but much
left unused. The problem is worse in some development zones.
</P>
<P>
During the freeze, SLA will strive to improve land management
and legislation to stop the sharp reduction of farmland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970615.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Exporters Need Credit Insurance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 15 (Xinhua) -- China needs to increase export
credit insurance services to protect exporters' interests, as the
country's foreign trade is soaring, today's China Daily quoted a
Chinese Academy of Social Sciences (CASS) economist as saying.
</P>
<P>
Only 1.1 percent of exports are guaranteed by export credit
insurance, and the insured exporters account for 2.7 percent of
the foreign trade companies, said Yu Lixin of CASS's Institute of
Finance and Trade Economics.
</P>
<P>
Some enterprises can't collect their money quickly after
exporting, resulting in the loss of several hundred million US
dollars annually. "It shows China's export credit insurance is in
its infancy, but it also indicates its huge potential for
expansion," Yu said.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign trade scored 289.9 billion US dollars last
year, and is expected to hit 310 billion US dollars this year,
demanding development of export credit insurance.
</P>
<P>
"To maintain the high growth, the country's foreign trade must
keep in line with international practices," he said.
</P>
<P>
By insuring the exports or fund-raising for exports, the
insured exporters can be compensated if they aren't paid by the
buyers, as the insurance is a financial practice generally
supported by governments.
</P>
<P>
The People's Insurance (Property) Company of China (PICC) and
Export-Import Bank of China are entrusted by the government to
conduct export insurance services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970615.0143 </DOCNO>
