<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaragua Concerned With U.S. Resumption of Deportation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, June 14 (Xinhua) -- The Nicaraguan government today
expressed its concern over the United States' decision to resume
its deportation of Nicaraguans illegally residing there.
</P>
<P>
"The government of the Nicaraguan Republic expects the United
States government will use its discretional authority to stop the
deportations of Nicaraguans until the Miami Federal Court issues a
final determination on the case," the Nicaraguan Foreign Relations
Ministry said in a communique.
</P>
<P>
Federal Court of Miami Judge James Lawrence King failed to
extend the term of the judicial provision that impeded the
deportation of Nicaraguans, thus signaling the resumption of the
deportation.
</P>
<P>
But King said that is not a final decision.
</P>
<P>
Nicaragua requested the U.S. immigration authorities to listen
to King, who said he expected the immigration authorities not to
start deportations immediately.
</P>
<P>
The communique said it "sees with concern the fact that three
Nicaraguan citizens, deported by the United States, will arrive in
Managua tomorrow."
</P>
<P>
"The Nicaraguan government is confident the U.S. government, on
the basis of the excellent bilateral relations of the two
countries, will use its discretional administrative power to find
a positive and definitive solution to the thousands of Nicaraguans
who found their second home in that country," the communique
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
