<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schumacher Grabs Pole Position </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 14 (Xinhua) -- Michael Schumacher upstaged local
hero Jacques Villeneuve as he grabbed pole position for Sunday's
Canadian Formula One Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
The two-time world champion piloted his Ferrari on the limit
during Saturday's qualifying session to wrest the advantage from
his arch-rival with one of the greatest qualifying drives of his
career.
</P>
<P>
The German claimed his 15th career pole in clocking one minute
18.095 seconds, just 0.13 seconds faster than Villeneuve.
</P>
<P>
The 26-year-old Canadian faces an uphill task after seeing
Schumacher surge late to rob him of what would have been his sixth
pole in seven races this season.
</P>
<P>
Villenueve seemed set to take the crucial place at the head of
the grid late on, only to be denied when the session was
re-started after rookie Alexander Wurz -- deputising for the ill
Gerhard Berger -- crashed his Benetton-Renault.
</P>
<P>
The pacesetting duo were on the track together in the final
minutes with Schumacher almost crashing into the perimeter wall as
he came round the final corner before scorching down the straight
to just dip under Villeneuve's time.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian Rubens Barrichello was third-fastest in a
Stewart-Ford with Heinz-Harald Frentzen of Germany fourth-quickest
in the second Williams-Renault after being fastest in Friday's
free practice session.
</P>
<P>
Villeneuve, who has won three of the six races so far this
season, leads the world championship with 30 points going into
Sunday's race. Schumacher, a winner only once but a points-scorer
in five of his six starts, has 27 points.
</P>
<P>
Sunday's race will be over 69 laps of the 4.421 Circuit Gilles
Villeneuve -- named in honor of Jacques Villeneueve's late father,
who died during practice for the Belgian Grand Prix at Zolder 15
years ago -- a total of 305.04km. 
</P>
</TEXT>
