<HEADLINE> Latin American Cultural Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are the
highlights of Latin American cultural news in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- The members of the New York Philharmonic
Orchestra, the oldest U.S. symphonic orchestra, had arrived
in Argentina and would offer three concerts.
</P>
<P>
Their programs would include traditional works of Wagner,
Tchaikovski and Bruckner, as well as contemporaneous works of Paul
Hindemith and George Gershwin.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- The Mexican Cultural Center in Paris had held an
exhibition in which fifteen Mexican artists' paintings and
sculptures were put on display.
</P>
<P>
The holding of the exhibition was aimed at collecting funds for
public welfare institutions.
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- Eighty poets from 38 countries were taking
part in the seventh International Poetry Festival of Medellin held
here and would read their works in their native languages.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The Uruguayan Chamber of Deputies had approved a
law project under which the "La Cumparsita" tango would be
declared as the cultural and popular anthem of Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
The melody had been created by Uruguayan composer Gerardo
Hernan Matos Rodriguez and premiered in Montevideo in April of
1917.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Three 300-year-old mummies discovered in 1960s at
Itacambira in the southeastern Brazilian state of Minas Gerais
will be exhibited for the first time in Rio de Janeiro.
</P>
<P>
The mummies, a woman, a man, and a one-year-old infant, got
mummified in a natural way because of the dry climate in
Itacambira.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- The programs of violence in television were
rejected by 41.5 percent of Chileans, the National Television
Council of Chile said in a study. 
</P>
</TEXT>
